{
  "texts": [
    "This \"Time-Dependent Hartree-Fock (TDHF) equation\" was first written down by Dirac in 1930 [218].",
    "Importantly, the TDHF time evolution conserves energy:Ė = d dt tr P T + 1 2 (H H [P] + H F [P]) (65) = tr Ṗ T + 1 2 (H H [P] + H F [P]) + 1 2 tr P (H H [ Ṗ] + H F [ Ṗ])(66)= tr Ṗ T + 1 2 (H H [P] + H F [P]) + 1 2 tr (H H [P] + H F [P]) Ṗ (67) = tr Ṗ H HF [P] (68) = 0,(69)where the last line follows directly from Ṗ = -i[H HF [P], P].",
    "This energy conservation is no coincidence, but follows from the fact that the TDHF equation can be interpreted as a time-dependent variational equation, as we explain in the following section.",
    "We will closely follow the exposition of Ref.",
    "Time-dependent Variational Principle with Slater DeterminantsGiven a Slater determinant |ψ 0 ⟩ (for example the one which solves the Hartree-Fock self-consistency equation for the problem of interest), one can parametrize all Slater determinants which have non-zero overlap with |ψ 0 ⟩ as|ψ(z)⟩ = exp   m,i z im ĉ † m ĉi   |ψ 0 ⟩ = exp ĉ † Z T ĉ |ψ 0 ⟩."
  ]
}